{{Quote|The caste nearest the great god, Yun-Yuuzhan, who shaped the universe from his body. It is they who know the ways of life, who bend it to our needs.|[[Vua Rapuung]]|<ref name="The New Jedi Order: Edge of Victory I: Conquest">''[[The New Jedi Order: Edge of Victory I: Conquest]]''</ref>}}
The '''shaper caste''' was the [[Yuuzhan Vong castes|caste]] responsible for creating all things used by the [[Yuuzhan Vong]].

==Overview==
{{Quote|Fy'y Roog! Fy'y Roog!|The battle cry of the shapers|<ref name="The New Jedi Order: Destiny's Way">''[[The New Jedi Order: Destiny's Way]]''</ref>}}
This class in Yuuzhan Vong society was considered the equivalent of bioengineers and [[Scientist/Legends|scientists]]. From the mighty [[Koros-Strohna]] to simple clothing, the shapers made everything, and techniques were written in instructions known as cortexes, of which there were [[Eighth cortex|eight]]. Adepts were only allowed access to information up to the Fifth cortex; only Masters could give access to the higher ones.

The shapers were guided by strict protocols, and deviance from these protocols was grounds for demotion to another caste, or death. This was due to the Yuuzhan Vong religious beliefs which stated that knowledge was incapable of being created as it was given to them from the mind of [[Yun-Yuuzhan]] through [[Yun-Harla]]'s handmaiden [[Yun-Ne'Shel]]. This caused a serious lack of ingenuity and inventiveness on the part of the shapers.
[[File:NenYim3.jpg|thumb|left|180px|The Shaper [[Nen Yim]]]]

This caste worshiped a particular deity among the pantheon of the [[Yun'o]], which was Yun-Ne'Shel, the Modeler. Just as the [[warrior caste]] emulated [[Yun-Yammka]], the shapers attempted to model themselves after their goddess. This meant that they did not have excessive outward scarring but instead made use of necessary ones. As such, they were often fully tattooed, wore form-fitting [[oozhith]]s and had [[Shaper headdress|special headdresses]] that displayed their rudimentary emotional state, though at times they were capable of controlling the display of the headdress's tentacles.

When [[Initiate (Shaper)|Shaper Initiates]] entered the rank of Adept, they were required to make their sacrifices to the gods. This involved them being in the [[Grotto of Yun-Ne'Shel]], where they sacrificed a hand to the organic creature, which was replaced with a [[Shaper hand]] that would aid them in shaping new creatures. Furthermore, there was the implantation of a [[Vaa-tumor]], which was painful over the years but remodeled their brain to accept the knowledge they learned during their training. The tumor was believed to sculpt their brains to match the divine form of Yun-Ne'Shel, and by the time they became a Master Shaper, the tumor was required to be removed. Some, however, held an emotional connection to the tumor and were ashamed to admit that they were saddened to see it removed in the ceremony.

==History==
[[File:Swlegacy12.jpg|180px|thumb|[[Nei Rin]], a Master Shaper in the [[Fel Empire]] era]]
{{Quote|As warriors take on the outward aspects of Yun-Yammka, so we take the inner qualities of Yun-Ne'Shel, she-who-shapes.|Master Shaper Mezhan Kwaad to Nen Yim|<ref name="The New Jedi Order: Edge of Victory I: Conquest" />}}
During the [[Yuuzhan Vong War]], the invaders made a number of victories against the infidels of the [[New Republic/Legends|New Republic]] thanks to their organic technology. However, as the war progressed, their enemies developed mechanical solutions to the Yuuzhan Vong technology while the [[Yuuzhan Vong empire]] was stagnant in its development, which meant that they might have lost the war if their enemy continued to progress technologically.

After continued exposure to the Jedi, the Yuuzhan Vong became intensely interested in this new foe due to their perceived powers from [[The Force/Legends|the Force]]. As all Yuuzhan Vong were blind to it yet saw its usage by the Jedi, they feared this threat. Thus, a number of shaper sects were assigned to deal with the Jedi "problem". They eventually learned of [[Emperor/Legends|Emperor]] [[Palpatine/Legends|Palpatine]], the [[Dark side of the Force/Legends|dark side of the Force]] and [[Wayland/Legends|Wayland]], where they attempted to find clues through which they could destroy the Jedi threat. This meant that a number of holy programs were developed, which included the attempted Shaping of the Jedi [[Tahiri Veila]] and the creation of the [[voxyn]] from the [[vornskr]]s. Another plot by the [[Viith Yalu|Shapers]] involved the poisoning of the [[Bacta/Legends|bacta]] supply on [[Thyferra/Legends|Thyferra]].

As the invasion progressed, [[Supreme Overlord]] [[Shimrra Jamaane]] recruited the Shaper Adept [[Nen Yim]], who had been convicted of heresy due to the actions of her master, [[Mezhan Kwaad]]. She was secretly placed in a development program to create new shaping techniques and fill the Eighth cortex with new knowledge as it was nearly empty, something that the vast majority of the Yuuzhan Vong were unaware of.

The shaper caste was heavily involved in the shaping of the galactic [[Capital/Legends|capital]] of [[Coruscant/Legends|Coruscant]] and reforming it as a simulacrum of their long-lost [[Homeworld/Legends|homeworld]] of [[Yuuzhan'tar]]. They were also involved in fixing a number of problems that seemed to originate from the [[World Brain]].

After the war, the shapers joined their caste brethren by leaving in peace and settling on the living planet [[Zonama Sekot/Legends|Zonama Sekot]] which departed into the [[Unknown Regions/Legends|Unknown Regions]]. The Shapers eventually made contact with the [[New Jedi Order]] and were asked to help in the [[Ossus Project]]; an initiative to terraform destroyed planets. However, their efforts were sabotaged by the [[One Sith]] and their people were made scapegoats by the inhabitants of the galaxy.

Other shapers living outside of Yuuzhan Vong society on Sekot employed their skills to the inhabitants of the galaxy at large. Although Yuuzhan Vong biots were illegal, enhancements by shapers were desired by the likes of [[Pirate/Legends|pirates]] and (very rarely) Imperial [[Officer/Legends|officers]]. Despite being a Yuuzhan Vong art, other species could preform shaping with the right training.<ref name="Legacy 2006 44">[[Legacy (2006) 44|''Legacy'' (2006) 44]]</ref>

==Development==
Author [[Greg Keyes]] has indicated that the introduction of the shapers was to bring a more multi-faceted element to Yuuzhan Vong society for readers of the series, saying, ''"Up until then, the Yuuzhan Vong had just been portrayed as sadomasochistic. There wasn't anything about them that was relatable. We had only seen a couple of the castes; we hadn't seen the shapers. I think explicitly they wanted me to come up with stuff about the shaper caste. I think they did choose me for my background with other cultures. I think, initially after the shock-and-awe, they wanted to make the Yuuzhan Vong a little more complicated."''<ref name=":0">{{YouTube|video=AiNTRIfprJQ|text=Crafting An Epic: The Making of the New Jedi Order &#124; Part III: Recoil &#124; Star Wars Documentary|channel=@holonetwork|name=holonet|date=2025-01-20}}</ref>

Keyes, an anthropologist himself, was greatly influenced by the ancient [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Austronesian_peoples Austronesians], as well as by their descendant peoples, the [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Melanesians Melanesians] and [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polynesians Polynesians], in further developing the shaper caste. Even specific names of the shapers, such as Mezhan Kwaad, were directly inspired by the names and myths of Pacific origin. The tattoos and piercings of Nen Yim, as depicted on the covers of [[The New Jedi Order: Edge of Victory I: Conquest|''Edge of Victory: Conquest'']] and [[The New Jedi Order: The Final Prophecy|''The Final Prophecy'']], also bear a resemblance to those found amongst the indigenous cultures of Oceania; cover artist [[Terese Nielsen]] had Keyes' guidance in shaping the look of the character for those covers.<ref name=":0" />

